<Layout title="Private Sale vs Real Estate Agent in Brisbane: An Honest Comparison | Daniel Gierach Property" description="A balanced look at selling your Brisbane property privately versus through a real estate agent — what FSBO actually involves, where it tends to fall short, and when it might make sense." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I sell my house privately in Queensland without a real estate agent?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. There is no legal requirement to use a real estate agent to sell a residential property in Queensland. You can list on FSBO platforms or major portals (in some cases), negotiate directly with buyers, and engage a solicitor or conveyancer to handle the contract and settlement. However, most property portals require a licensed agent for listings, which limits private sellers' marketing reach."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much do I save by selling privately instead of using an agent in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The saving depends on the commission rate you would have paid an agent — typically 2% to 3% of the sale price in Brisbane. On a $1,000,000 property, that is $20,000 to $30,000. However, the relevant comparison is not between agent commission and zero cost — it is between your likely net sale price with an agent versus without one. If an agent achieves even 3% to 5% more than you would privately, the commission is recouped."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are the biggest risks of selling privately in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The main risks are limited marketing reach (no access to the agent's buyer database), reduced buyer competition (which directly affects price), negotiating directly with buyers without professional support, and the legal complexity of contract preparation and disclosure obligations. Private sellers also tend to underestimate the time required to manage enquiries, inspections, and negotiations."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

